[36;1mDESCRIPTION[0m
       A mutex is a MUTual EXclusion device,  and  is  useful  for  protecting
       shared  data structures from concurrent modifications, and implementing
       critical sections and monitors.

       A mutex has two possible states: unlocked (not owned  by  any  thread),
       and  locked  (owned  by one thread).  A mutex can never be owned by two
       different threads simultaneously.  A thread attempting to lock a  mutex
       that  is already locked by another thread is suspended until the owning
       thread unlocks the mutex first.

       [36;1mpthread_mutex_init[22;0m() initializes the mutex object pointed to  by  [31;3;1mmutex[0m
       according to the mutex attributes specified in [31;3;1mmutexattr[24;0m.  If [31;3;1mmutexattr[0m
       is NULL, default attributes are used instead.

       The LinuxThreads implementation supports only one mutex attributes, the
       [31;3;1mmutex[24;0m  [31;3;1mkind[24;0m,  which is either "fast", "recursive", or "error checking".
       The kind of a mutex determines whether it can  be  locked  again  by  a
       thread  that  already  owns  it.   The  default  kind  is  "fast".  See
       [36;1mpthread_mutexattr_init[22;0m(3) for more information on mutex attributes.

       Variables of type [31;3;1mpthread_mutex_t[24;0m can also be  initialized  statically,
       using  the  constants  [36;1mPTHREAD_MUTEX_INITIALIZER  [22;0m(for  fast  mutexes),
       [36;1mPTHREAD_RECURSIVE_MUTEX_INITIALIZER_NP  [22;0m(for  recursive  mutexes),  and
       [36;1mPTHREAD_ERRORCHECK_MUTEX_INITIALIZER_NP [22;0m(for error checking mutexes).

       [36;1mpthread_mutex_lock[22;0m()  locks the given mutex.  If the mutex is currently
       unlocked, it becomes locked  and  owned  by  the  calling  thread,  and
       [36;1mpthread_mutex_lock[22;0m()  returns  immediately.   If  the  mutex is already
       locked by another thread,  [36;1mpthread_mutex_lock[22;0m()  suspends  the  calling
       thread until the mutex is unlocked.

       If  the  mutex is already locked by the calling thread, the behavior of
       [36;1mpthread_mutex_lock[22;0m() depends on the kind of the mutex.  If the mutex is
       of the "fast" kind, the calling thread is suspended until the mutex  is
       unlocked,  thus effectively causing the calling thread to deadlock.  If
       the mutex is of the "error checking" kind, [36;1mpthread_mutex_lock[22;0m() returns
       immediately with the error code [36;1mEDEADLK[22;0m.  If the mutex is of  the  "re‐
       cursive"  kind,  [36;1mpthread_mutex_lock[22;0m() succeeds and returns immediately,
       recording the number of times the calling thread has locked the  mutex.
       An  equal number of [36;1mpthread_mutex_unlock[22;0m() operations must be performed
       before the mutex returns to the unlocked state.

       [36;1mpthread_mutex_trylock[22;0m() behaves  identically  to  [36;1mpthread_mutex_lock[22;0m(),
       except  that  it  does not block the calling thread if the mutex is al‐
       ready locked by another thread (or by the calling thread in the case of
       a "fast" mutex).  Instead, [36;1mpthread_mutex_trylock[22;0m() returns  immediately
       with the error code [36;1mEBUSY[22;0m.

       [36;1mpthread_mutex_unlock[22;0m()  unlocks  the given mutex.  The mutex is assumed
       to be locked and owned by the calling thread on entrance to [36;1mpthread_mu‐[0m
       [36;1mtex_unlock[22;0m().  If the mutex is of the  "fast"  kind,  [36;1mpthread_mutex_un‐[0m
       [36;1mlock[22;0m()  always  returns it to the unlocked state.  If it is of the "re‐
       cursive" kind, it decrements the locking count of the mutex (number  of
       [36;1mpthread_mutex_lock[22;0m() operations performed on it by the calling thread),
       and only when this count reaches zero is the mutex actually unlocked.

       On "error checking" and "recursive" mutexes, [36;1mpthread_mutex_unlock[22;0m() ac‐
       tually  checks  at  run‐time  that the mutex is locked on entrance, and
       that it was locked by the same thread that is now  calling  [36;1mpthread_mu‐[0m
       [36;1mtex_unlock[22;0m().   If  these  conditions are not met, an error code is re‐
       turned and the mutex remains unchanged.  "Fast" mutexes perform no such
       checks, thus allowing a locked mutex to be unlocked by a  thread  other
       than  its  owner.  This is non‐portable behavior and must not be relied
       upon.

       [36;1mpthread_mutex_destroy[22;0m() destroys a mutex object, freeing the  resources
       it  might hold.  The mutex must be unlocked on entrance.  In the Linux‐
       Threads implementation, no resources are associated with mutex objects,
       thus [36;1mpthread_mutex_destroy[22;0m() actually does nothing except checking that
       the mutex is unlocked.

[36;1mCANCELLATION[0m
       None  of  the  mutex  functions  is  a  cancelation  point,  not   even
       [36;1mpthread_mutex_lock[22;0m(), in spite of the fact that it can suspend a thread
       for  arbitrary  durations.  This way, the status of mutexes at cancela‐
       tion points is predictable, allowing  cancelation  handlers  to  unlock
       precisely  those  mutexes  that  need  to be unlocked before the thread
       stops executing.   Consequently,  threads  using  deferred  cancelation
       should never hold a mutex for extended periods of time.

[36;1mASYNC‐SIGNAL SAFETY[0m
       The mutex functions are not async‐signal safe.  What this means is that
       they  should not be called from a signal handler.  In particular, call‐
       ing [36;1mpthread_mutex_lock[22;0m() or [36;1mpthread_mutex_unlock[22;0m() from a  signal  han‐
       dler may deadlock the calling thread.

[36;1mRETURN VALUE[0m
       [36;1mpthread_mutex_init[22;0m()  always  returns 0.  The other mutex functions re‐
       turn 0 on success and a non‐zero error code on error.

[36;1mERRORS[0m
       The [36;1mpthread_mutex_lock[22;0m() function returns the following error  code  on
       error:

              [36;1mEINVAL [22;0mThe mutex has not been properly initialized.

              [36;1mEDEADLK[0m
                     The mutex is already locked by the calling thread ("error
                     checking" mutexes only).

       The  [36;1mpthread_mutex_trylock[22;0m() function returns the following error codes
       on error:

              [36;1mEBUSY  [22;0mThe mutex could not be acquired because it was  currently
                     locked.

              [36;1mEINVAL [22;0mThe mutex has not been properly initialized.

       The [36;1mpthread_mutex_unlock[22;0m() function returns the following error code on
       error:

              [36;1mEINVAL [22;0mThe mutex has not been properly initialized.

              [36;1mEPERM  [22;0mThe  calling thread does not own the mutex ("error check‐
                     ing" mutexes only).

       The [36;1mpthread_mutex_destroy[22;0m() function returns the following  error  code
       on error:

              [36;1mEBUSY  [22;0mThe mutex is currently locked.

